{"title_page": "Harvey Milk Lesbian / Gay / Bisexual / Transgender / Queer Democratic Club", "text_new": "{{other uses|Harvey Milk (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Harvey-Milk-Club-Logo.jpg|thumb|Logo of the organization<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.milkclub.org/|title=Harvey Milk LGBT Democratic Club|website=Harvey Milk LGBT Democratic Club|language=en|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref>]]\nBased in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], the '''Harvey Milk Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer Democratic Club''' is a chapter of the [[Stonewall Democrats]], named after [[LGBT]] politician and activist [[Harvey Milk]]. Believing that the existing [[Alice B. Toklas LGBT Democratic Club]] would never support him in his political aspirations, Milk co-founded the club under the name \"San Francisco Gay Democratic Club\" in the wake of his unsuccessful 1976 campaign for the [[California State Assembly]]. Joining Milk in forming the club were a number of the city's activists, including [[Harry Britt]], [[Dick Pabich]], Jim Rivaldo, and first club president Chris Perry.<ref name = shilts150>Shilts (1982), p. 150</ref>\n\nThe club set forth the following as its organizing statement:\n<blockquote>No decisions which affect our lives should be made without the gay voice being heard. We want our fair share of city services. We want openly gay people appointed and elected to city offices\u2014people who reflect the diversity of our community. We want the schools of San Francisco to provide full exposure to and positive appreciation of gay lifestyles. We are asking no more than we deserve: We will not settle for less.<ref name = shilts150 /></blockquote>\n\n==History==\nOne of the club's early actions was to demonstrate at a speech given by Vice President [[Walter Mondale]] in [[Golden Gate Park]] on June 17, 1977. When Mondale began speaking about human rights in Latin America, demonstrators held up signs demanding a statement on human rights in the United States. When a demonstrator verbally challenged Mondale to say something about gay rights, Mondale angrily left the stage.<ref>Shilts (1982), p. 161</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Moscone-Milk assassinations|assassination of Harvey Milk]] in 1978, the club changed its name to the Harvey Milk Democratic Club in his memory. The club bills itself as one of the largest Democratic clubs in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title = The Harvey Milk Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer Democratic Club\n  | publisher = The Harvey Milk Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer Democratic Club\n  | date = March 2019\n  | url = http://www.milkclub.org/about\n  | accessdate = 2019-03-09}}</ref>\n\nThe club was an inadvertent catalyst of a [[journalistic scandal]] for [[CBS]]. CBS News producers [[George Crile III|George Crile]] and [[Grace Diekhaus]] manipulated footage of an appearance by [[Dianne Feinstein]] and included it in the 1980 documentary ''[[Gay Power, Gay Politics]]''. The [[National News Council]] found that this manipulation was a breach of journalistic ethics.<ref>Rutledge, p. 152</ref>\n\nWith the onset of the [[AIDS]] epidemic, the Milk Club was an early advocate of closing down the city's [[gay bathhouse]]s. The club also created some of the earliest [[safe sex]] education materials in the country.<ref>Shilts (1987), p. 280</ref>\n\n==SFPD Apology==\n\nShortly before San Francisco's annual [[Pride parade]] in 2019, a year that marked the 40th anniversary of the [[White Night riots]], the Milk Club's Executive Board penned an open letter<ref>{{cite web |title=SFPD Apology Letter |url=http://www.milkclub.org/sfpd_apology_letter |website=Milkclub.org |publisher=Harvey Milk LGBTQ Democratic Club}}</ref> calling on the [[San Francisco Police Department]] to apologize for historic acts of violence against the city's LGBTQ community, including the ACT UP Castro Sweep in 1989,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Koskovich |first1=Gerard |title=Remembering A Police Riot: The Castro Sweep of October 6, 1989 |url=http://www.foundsf.org/index.php?title=Remembering_A_Police_Riot:_The_Castro_Sweep_of_October_6,_1989 |publisher=Found SF}}</ref> the White Night Riot in 1979, and the [[Compton's Cafeteria riot]] in 1966.\n\nDuring San Francisco's 2019 Pride parade, the SFPD engaged in a violent confrontation with a group of LGBTQ protestors who blocked the parade, calling for an end to corporate sponsorships of Pride. The Milk Club released another letter shortly after, condemning the SFPD's actions at Pride. \u201cThe irony of SFPD committing acts of brutality against peaceful protesters of the Resistance Contingent at the San Francisco Pride Parade on the 50th Anniversary of Stonewall is not lost on us,\u201d the Milk Club wrote. \u201cIt warrants outrage and swift recourse.\u201d <ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitzgerald-Rodriguez |first1=Joe |title=Advocates call for SFPD to apologize for past attacks on gay community \u2014 and this weekend\u2019s arrests as well |url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/news-columnists/advocates-call-for-sfpd-to-apologize-for-past-attacks-on-gay-community-and-this-weekends-arrests-as-well/ |publisher=San Francisco Examiner |date=2019-01-07}}</ref>\n\nOn August 26, 2019, SFPD leadership held a community meeting during which Chief William Scott said, \"we the members of the San Francisco Police Department are here to reflect and apologize for our past actions against the LGBTQ community. We want to listen to you and want to truly hear you, we will atone for our past.\u201d While Scott's apology was met with \"exuberant applause from the room,\" some attendees at the meeting expressed their concern about the ways in which the SFPD currently discriminates against LGBTQ people.\n\nAnubis Daugherty, a young LGBTQ community member who was homeless for six years, told Scott that LGBTQ people are disproportionately caught up in sweeps of homeless communities in The City. \u201cI was born here, I was raised here,\u201d Daugherty said. \u201cIf you want to truly apologize for something you have to stop what you\u2019re doing.\u201d <ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitzgerald-Rodriguez |first1=Joe |title=SF police chief apologizes for \u2018past actions\u2019 against transgender community |url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/sf-police-chief-apologizes-for-historic-abuse-against-transgender-community/ |publisher=San Francisco Examiner |date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alice B. Toklas LGBT Democratic Club]]\n*[[National Stonewall Democrats]]\n\n==References==\n* Rutledge, Leigh (1992). ''The Gay Decades''. New York, Penguin. {{ISBN|0-452-26810-9}}.\n* {{cite book|last=Shilts|first=Randy|title=The Mayor of Castro Street|url=https://archive.org/details/mayorofcastrostr00shil_0|url-access=registration|year=1982|publisher=St. Martin's Press|location=New York|isbn=0-312-52331-9}}\n* Shilts, Randy (1987). ''And The Band Played On''. New York, St. Martin's Press. {{ISBN|0-312-00994-1}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.milkclub.org/ Harvey Milk Lesbian Gay Bisexual Transgender Democratic Club official site]\n* [http://www.stonewalldemocrats.org/ Stonewall Democrats official site]\n{{Harvey Milk}}\n{{LGBT|history=yes}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT liberalism]]\n[[Category:LGBT political advocacy groups in California]]\n[[Category:California Democratic Party]]\n[[Category:LGBT affiliate organizations of political parties]]\n[[Category:Harvey Milk]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (United States) organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Harvey Milk (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Harvey-Milk-Club-Logo.jpg|thumb|Logo of the organization<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.milkclub.org/|title=Harvey Milk LGBT Democratic Club|website=Harvey Milk LGBT Democratic Club|language=en|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref>]]\nBased in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], the '''Harvey Milk Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer Democratic Club''' is a chapter of the [[Stonewall Democrats]], named after [[LGBT]] politician and activist [[Harvey Milk]]. Believing that the existing [[Alice B. Toklas LGBT Democratic Club]] would never support him in his political aspirations, Milk cofounded the club under the name \"San Francisco Gay Democratic Club\" in the wake of his unsuccessful 1976 campaign for the [[California State Assembly]]. Joining Milk in forming the club were a number of the city's activists, including [[Harry Britt]], [[Dick Pabich]], Jim Rivaldo, and first club president Chris Perry.<ref name = shilts150>Shilts (1982), p. 150</ref>\n\nThe club set forth the following as its organizing statement:\n<blockquote>No decisions which affect our lives should be made without the gay voice being heard. We want our fair share of city services. We want openly gay people appointed and elected to city offices\u2014people who reflect the diversity of our community. We want the schools of San Francisco to provide full exposure to and positive appreciation of gay lifestyles. We are asking no more than we deserve: We will not settle for less.<ref name = shilts150 /></blockquote>\n\n==History==\nOne of the club's early actions was to demonstrate at a speech given by Vice President [[Walter Mondale]] in [[Golden Gate Park]] on June 17, 1977. When Mondale began speaking about human rights in Latin America, demonstrators held up signs demanding a statement on human rights in the United States. When a demonstrator verbally challenged Mondale to say something about gay rights, Mondale angrily left the stage.<ref>Shilts (1982), p. 161</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Moscone-Milk assassinations|assassination of Harvey Milk]] in 1978, the club changed its name to the Harvey Milk Democratic Club in his memory. The club bills itself as one of the largest Democratic clubs in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title = The Harvey Milk Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer Democratic Club\n  | publisher = The Harvey Milk Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer Democratic Club\n  | date = March 2019\n  | url = http://www.milkclub.org/about\n  | accessdate = 2019-03-09}}</ref>\n\nThe club was an inadvertent catalyst of a [[journalistic scandal]] for [[CBS]]. CBS News producers [[George Crile III|George Crile]] and [[Grace Diekhaus]] manipulated footage of an appearance by [[Dianne Feinstein]] and included it in the 1980 documentary ''[[Gay Power, Gay Politics]]''. The [[National News Council]] found that this manipulation was a breach of journalistic ethics.<ref>Rutledge, p. 152</ref>\n\nWith the onset of the [[AIDS]] epidemic, the Milk Club was an early advocate of closing down the city's [[gay bathhouse]]s. The club also created some of the earliest [[safe sex]] education materials in the country.<ref>Shilts (1987), p. 280</ref>\n\n==SFPD Apology==\n\nShortly before San Francisco's annual [[Pride parade]] in 2019, a year that marked the 40th anniversary of the [[White Night riots]], the Milk Club's Executive Board penned an open letter<ref>{{cite web |title=SFPD Apology Letter |url=http://www.milkclub.org/sfpd_apology_letter |website=Milkclub.org |publisher=Harvey Milk LGBTQ Democratic Club}}</ref> calling on the [[San Francisco Police Department]] to apologize for historic acts of violence against the city's LGBTQ community, including the ACT UP Castro Sweep in 1989,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Koskovich |first1=Gerard |title=Remembering A Police Riot: The Castro Sweep of October 6, 1989 |url=http://www.foundsf.org/index.php?title=Remembering_A_Police_Riot:_The_Castro_Sweep_of_October_6,_1989 |publisher=Found SF}}</ref> the White Night Riot in 1979, and the [[Compton's Cafeteria riot]] in 1966.\n\nDuring San Francisco's 2019 Pride parade, the SFPD engaged in a violent confrontation with a group of LGBTQ protestors who blocked the parade, calling for an end to corporate sponsorships of Pride. The Milk Club released another letter shortly after, condemning the SFPD's actions at Pride. \u201cThe irony of SFPD committing acts of brutality against peaceful protesters of the Resistance Contingent at the San Francisco Pride Parade on the 50th Anniversary of Stonewall is not lost on us,\u201d the Milk Club wrote. \u201cIt warrants outrage and swift recourse.\u201d <ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitzgerald-Rodriguez |first1=Joe |title=Advocates call for SFPD to apologize for past attacks on gay community \u2014 and this weekend\u2019s arrests as well |url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/news-columnists/advocates-call-for-sfpd-to-apologize-for-past-attacks-on-gay-community-and-this-weekends-arrests-as-well/ |publisher=San Francisco Examiner |date=2019-01-07}}</ref>\n\nOn August 26, 2019, SFPD leadership held a community meeting during which Chief William Scott said, \"we the members of the San Francisco Police Department are here to reflect and apologize for our past actions against the LGBTQ community. We want to listen to you and want to truly hear you, we will atone for our past.\u201d While Scott's apology was met with \"exuberant applause from the room,\" some attendees at the meeting expressed their concern about the ways in which the SFPD currently discriminates against LGBTQ people.\n\nAnubis Daugherty, a young LGBTQ community member who was homeless for six years, told Scott that LGBTQ people are disproportionately caught up in sweeps of homeless communities in The City. \u201cI was born here, I was raised here,\u201d Daugherty said. \u201cIf you want to truly apologize for something you have to stop what you\u2019re doing.\u201d <ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitzgerald-Rodriguez |first1=Joe |title=SF police chief apologizes for \u2018past actions\u2019 against transgender community |url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/news/sf-police-chief-apologizes-for-historic-abuse-against-transgender-community/ |publisher=San Francisco Examiner |date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alice B. Toklas LGBT Democratic Club]]\n*[[National Stonewall Democrats]]\n\n==References==\n* Rutledge, Leigh (1992). ''The Gay Decades''. New York, Penguin. {{ISBN|0-452-26810-9}}.\n* {{cite book|last=Shilts|first=Randy|title=The Mayor of Castro Street|url=https://archive.org/details/mayorofcastrostr00shil_0|url-access=registration|year=1982|publisher=St. Martin's Press|location=New York|isbn=0-312-52331-9}}\n* Shilts, Randy (1987). ''And The Band Played On''. New York, St. Martin's Press. {{ISBN|0-312-00994-1}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.milkclub.org/ Harvey Milk Lesbian Gay Bisexual Transgender Democratic Club official site]\n* [http://www.stonewalldemocrats.org/ Stonewall Democrats official site]\n{{Harvey Milk}}\n{{LGBT|history=yes}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT liberalism]]\n[[Category:LGBT political advocacy groups in California]]\n[[Category:California Democratic Party]]\n[[Category:LGBT affiliate organizations of political parties]]\n[[Category:Harvey Milk]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (United States) organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Jaing14", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvey_Milk_Lesbian_/_Gay_/_Bisexual_/_Transgender_/_Queer_Democratic_Club"}
{"title_page": "Under Construction (film)", "text_new": "{{more citations|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name =Under Construction\n| image = Poster Under-Construction.gif\n| caption = Poster of film\n| director =[[Rubaiyat Hossain]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Rubaiyat Hossain]]\n* [[Ashique Mostafa]]\n}}\n| writer =[[Rubaiyat Hossain]]\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Shahana Goswami]]\n* [[Rahul Bose]]\n* [[Rikita Nandini Shimu]]\n* [[Mita Rahman]]\n}}\n| cinematography  = Martina Radwan\n| distributor = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Khona Talkies (Bangladesh)]]\n* [[contre-courant (France)]] \n}}\n| released = {{Film date|2015|11|22|df=y}}\n| runtime =88 minutes\n| country =[[Bangladesh]]\n| language =[[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n}}\n'''''Under Construction''''' ({{lang-bn|\u0986\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09a8\u09cd\u09b8\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u0995\u09b6\u09a8}}; and French title as '''''Les Lauriers-roses rouges''''') is a 2015 [[Cinema of Bangladesh|Bengali]] narrative feature film written and directed by [[Rubaiyat Hossain]].\n\n==Plot==\nStruggling to find herself in the sprawl of urban Bangladesh, Muslim theater actress Roya suffers from her husband's wish for children and traditional life. Not interested in motherhood, she decides to reconstruct a famous and politically minded play for modern times, reclaiming her identity, her freedom and her sexuality in the process.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Shahana Goswami]]\n* Rikita Nandini Shimu\n* Mita Rahman\n* [[Rahul Bose]]\n* [[Shahadat Hossain (actor)|Shahadat Hossain]]\n\n==Production==\nThis film is produced by a Bangladeshi Film Production Company Khona Talkies.\n\n==Release==\nThe movie released in Star Cineplex and other theaters in Dhaka on 22 January 2015 running for 4 weeks.\n<br>\nReleased in France on 7 June 2017 running for 6 weeks.\n\n==Festivals==\n* [[Seattle International Film Festival]] (New Directors Showcase)\n* [[Montreal World Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ffm-montreal.org/en/745-en_under-construction.html|title=movie-Under Construction|website=www.ffm-montreal.org}}</ref>\n* [[S\u00e3o Paulo International Film Festival]]\n* [[Stockholm Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stockholmfilmfestival.se/en/festival/2015/film/under_construction|title=Under Construction|website=Stockholm International Film Festival}}</ref>\n* [[Locarno Film Festival]] - Open Doors<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pardolive.ch/pardo/program/film.html?fid=888700&eid=69|title=Under Construction|website=www.pardolive.ch}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\n*Prix du Jury International, FICA Vesoul<ref name=\"ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemas-asie.com/fr/prix-du-jury-international.html|title=Prix du Jury international|first=|last=Laurine|website=www.cinemas-asie.com}}</ref>\n*Mentions sp\u00e9ciales de la critique, FICA Vesoul<ref name=\"ca\" />\n*Prix Emile Guimet, FICA Vesoul<ref name=\"ca\" /> (awarded by Guimet Museum in Paris)\n*Best Emerging Director Award, NY AAIFF<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aaiff.org/2016/films/under-construction/|title=Under Construction|website=Asian CineVision}}</ref>\n*Best Audience Award, Dhaka IFF\n*[[Bangladesh National Film Awards 2016]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/national-film-award-winners-announced-1558849|title=National Film Award winners announced|date=6 April 2018|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-05-30|language=en}}</ref>\n**Best Dialogue\n**Best Make-up\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Bangladeshi films]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language films]]\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi drama films]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more citations|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name =Under Construction\n[[File:Poster Under-Construction.gif|thumb|Poster of film]]\n| director =[[Rubaiyat Hossain]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Rubaiyat Hossain]]\n* [[Ashique Mostafa]]\n}}\n| writer =[[Rubaiyat Hossain]]\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Shahana Goswami]]\n* [[Rahul Bose]]\n* [[Rikita Nandini Shimu]]\n* [[Mita Rahman]]\n}}\n| cinematography  = Martina Radwan\n| distributor = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Khona Talkies (Bangladesh)]]\n* [[contre-courant (France)]] \n}}\n| released ={{Film date|2015}}\n| runtime =88 minutes\n| country =[[Bangladesh]]\n| language =[[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n}}\n'''''Under Construction''''' ({{lang-bn|\u0986\u09a8\u09cd\u09a1\u09be\u09b0 \u0995\u09a8\u09cd\u09b8\u099f\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u0995\u09b6\u09a8}}; and French title as '''''Les Lauriers-roses rouges''''') is a 2015 [[Cinema of Bangladesh|Bengali]] narrative feature film written and directed by [[Rubaiyat Hossain]].\n\n==Plot==\nStruggling to find herself in the sprawl of urban Bangladesh, Muslim theater actress Roya suffers from her husband's wish for children and traditional life. Not interested in motherhood, she decides to reconstruct a famous and politically minded play for modern times, reclaiming her identity, her freedom and her sexuality in the process.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Shahana Goswami]]\n* Rikita Nandini Shimu\n* Mita Rahman\n* [[Rahul Bose]]\n* [[Shahadat Hossain (actor)|Shahadat Hossain]]\n\n==Production==\nThis film is produced by a Bangladeshi Film Production Company Khona Talkies.\n\n==Release==\nThe movie released in Star Cineplex and other theaters in Dhaka on 22 January 2015 running for 4 weeks.\n<br>\nReleased in France on 7 June 2017 running for 6 weeks.\n\n==Festivals==\n* [[Seattle International Film Festival]] (New Directors Showcase)\n* [[Montreal World Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ffm-montreal.org/en/745-en_under-construction.html|title=movie-Under Construction|website=www.ffm-montreal.org}}</ref>\n* [[S\u00e3o Paulo International Film Festival]]\n* [[Stockholm Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stockholmfilmfestival.se/en/festival/2015/film/under_construction|title=Under Construction|website=Stockholm International Film Festival}}</ref>\n* [[Locarno Film Festival]] - Open Doors<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pardolive.ch/pardo/program/film.html?fid=888700&eid=69|title=Under Construction|website=www.pardolive.ch}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\n*Prix du Jury International, FICA Vesoul<ref name=\"ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemas-asie.com/fr/prix-du-jury-international.html|title=Prix du Jury international|first=|last=Laurine|website=www.cinemas-asie.com}}</ref>\n*Mentions sp\u00e9ciales de la critique, FICA Vesoul<ref name=\"ca\" />\n*Prix Emile Guimet, FICA Vesoul<ref name=\"ca\" /> (awarded by Guimet Museum in Paris)\n*Best Emerging Director Award, NY AAIFF<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aaiff.org/2016/films/under-construction/|title=Under Construction|website=Asian CineVision}}</ref>\n*Best Audience Award, Dhaka IFF\n*[[Bangladesh National Film Awards 2016]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/national-film-award-winners-announced-1558849|title=National Film Award winners announced|date=6 April 2018|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-05-30|language=en}}</ref>\n**Best Dialogue\n**Best Make-up\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Bangladeshi films]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language films]]\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi drama films]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bovineboy2008", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix image, add premiere date to infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Under_Construction_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Act. 1 The Little Mermaid", "text_new": "{{short description|2016 extended play by Gugudan}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Act. 1 The Little Mermaid\n| type       = EP\n| artist     = [[Gugudan]]\n| cover      = Act1TheLittleMermaid.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2016|06|28}}\n| recorded   = 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[K-pop]]\n| length     = 20:41\n| language   = [[Korean language|Korean]]\n| label      =  {{hlist|[[Jellyfish Entertainment|Jellyfish]]|[[CJ E&M Music Performance Division|CJ E&M]]}}\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Act. 2 Narcissus]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Act. 1 The Little Mermaid\n | type        = EP\n | single1     = Wonderland\n | single1date = {{Start date|2016|06|28}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Act. 1 The Little Mermaid''''' is the debut [[extended play]] by South Korean girl group [[Gugudan]]. It was released digitally and physically on June 28, 2016 by [[Jellyfish Entertainment]] and distributed by [[CJ E&M Music Performance Division|CJ E&M]].\nYou can read about mermeids eg.marko mermaids\n\n==Background and release==\nOn June 13, 2016, Jellyfish Entertainment launched the band's official website and announced via SNS that the group would debut with the mini-album Act. 1: The Little Mermaid and title-track \"Wonderland\".\n\nTeasers featuring each of the members for their music video were released from June 14 to 16, 2016. On June 28, the song's music video were released online and through the Naver V App.\n\nThe EP was released on June 28, 2016 on [[Melon (online music service)|Melon]] and various sites in South Korea and on [[ITunes Store|iTunes]] for the global market as a digital download.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.melon.com/album/detail.htm?albumId=2694101|title=\uc568\ubc94 \uc815\ubcf4>\uba5c\ub860|website=www.melon.com|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/act.1-the-little-mermaid-ep/id1128322245|title=Act.1 The Little Mermaid \u2013 EP by gugudan on Apple Music|website=iTunes|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nThe music video for the title track \"Wonderland\", was released on June 28, 2016 in conjunction with the EP and accumulates over 2 million views.<ref>{{Citation|last=CJENMMUSIC Official|title=\uad6c\uad6c\ub2e8 (gugudan) \u2013 Wonderland MV|date=2016-06-27|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ej-PBlE4ODQ|accessdate=2016-07-21}}</ref> Gugudan held a live showcase on June 28.\n\nOn June 29, the group made their official debut on [[MBC Music]]'s ''[[Show Champion]]'' performing \"Good Boy\" and \"Wonderland\".<ref>{{Citation|last=MBC MUSIC|title=(ShowChampion EP.192) gugudan \u2013 Good Boy|date=2016-06-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ykLu_ZhpYDM|accessdate=2016-07-21}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=MBC MUSIC|title=(ShowChampion EP.192) gugudan \u2013 Wonderland|date=2016-06-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8n7qIFevh94|accessdate=2016-07-21}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\n''Act. 1 The Little Mermaid'' entered and peaked at number 2 on the South Korean [[Gaon Album Chart]] on the chart issue dated June 26 \u2013 July 2, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=27&hitYear=2016&termGbn=week |title=\uad6d\ub0b4 \ub300\ud45c \uc74c\uc545 \ucc28\ud2b8 \uac00\uc628\ucc28\ud2b8! |website=gaonchart.co.kr |access-date=2016-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008145243/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=27&hitYear=2016&termGbn=week |archivedate=2016-10-08 }}</ref> In its third week, the EP re entered the Top 10 at number 8.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=29&hitYear=2016&termGbn=week|title=\uad6d\ub0b4 \ub300\ud45c \uc74c\uc545 \ucc28\ud2b8 \uac00\uc628\ucc28\ud2b8!|website=gaonchart.co.kr|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref> The EP also charted at number 8 on Gaon Album Chart for the month of June 2016 with 12,839 copies sold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&termGbn=month|title=\uad6d\ub0b4 \ub300\ud45c \uc74c\uc545 \ucc28\ud2b8 \uac00\uc628\ucc28\ud2b8!|website=gaonchart.co.kr|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref>\n\nThe title track \"Wonderland\" entered and peaked at number 38 on the South Korean [[Gaon Digital Chart]] on the chart issue dated June 26 \u2013 July 2, 2016 with 55,887 downloads sold and 703,642 streams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=27&hitYear=2016&termGbn=week|title=\uad6d\ub0b4 \ub300\ud45c \uc74c\uc545 \ucc28\ud2b8 \uac00\uc628\ucc28\ud2b8!|website=gaonchart.co.kr|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=S1020&targetTime=27&hitYear=2016&termGbn=week|title=\uad6d\ub0b4 \ub300\ud45c \uc74c\uc545 \ucc28\ud2b8 \uac00\uc628\ucc28\ud2b8!|website=gaonchart.co.kr|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=S1040&targetTime=27&hitYear=2016&termGbn=week|title=\uad6d\ub0b4 \ub300\ud45c \uc74c\uc545 \ucc28\ud2b8 \uac00\uc628\ucc28\ud2b8!|website=gaonchart.co.kr|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| title1          = Wonderland\n| lyrics1         = {{hlist|ButterFly|Jang Yeon-jung|Kim In-hyung}}\n| music1          = ButterFly\n| length1         = 3:05\n\n| title2          = Could This Be Love\n| note2           = \uad6c\ub984 \uc704\ub85c; ''Gureum Wiro''\n| lyrics2         = [[Misfit (songwriter)|Misfit]]\n| music2          = {{hlist|Simon Janl\u00f6v|[[Andreas Oberg]]|[[Kanata Okajima]]}}\n| length2         = 3:14\n\n| title3          = Good Boy\n| lyrics3         = {{hlist|Kim Chang-rak|Mario|Han Kyung-su}}\n| music3          = {{hlist|Kim Chang-rak|Park Su-seok|Lee Hyun-sang}}\n| length3         = 2:54\n\n| title4          = Diary\n| note4           = \uc77c\uae30; ''Ilgi''\n| lyrics4         = {{hlist|Jin-ri|Glory Face}}\n| music4          = {{hlist|Glory Face|Jin-ri|Ming-ki}}\n| length4         = 3:38\n\n| title5          = Maybe Tomorrow \n| lyrics5         = Kim Ji-hyang\n| music5          = MELODESIGN \n| length5         = 4:48\n\n| title6          = Wonderland\n| note6           = instrumental\n| lyrics6         = \n| music6          = ButterFly\n| length6         = 3:05\n\n| total_length    = 20:41\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Charts (2016)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |South Korean Albums ([[Gaon Album Chart|Gaon]])\n| align=\"center\" |2\n|}\n\n=== Monthly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (2016)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |South Korean Albums ([[Gaon Album Chart|Gaon]])\n| align=\"center\" |8\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Region !! Date !! Format !! Label\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Worldwide\n| rowspan=2| June 28, 2016\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| rowspan=2|[[Jellyfish Entertainment]], [[CJ E&M Music Performance Division|CJ E&M Music]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[South Korea]]\n| [[Compact Disc|CD]], music download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Taiwan]]<ref>[http://www.avex.com.tw/Artist/artist_disco_songlist.asp?CatalogNo=JF_GU_001 ''Act. 1 The Little Mermaid'']. Copyright 2016 [[Avex Taiwan|Avex Taiwan Inc.]]</ref>\n| June 29, 2016\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| [[Avex Taiwan|Avex Taiwan Inc.]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist }}\n{{Gugudan|state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Gugudan albums]]\n[[Category:2016 debut EPs]]\n[[Category:Korean-language EPs]]\n[[Category:Jellyfish Entertainment EPs]]\n[[Category:Fiction about mermaids]]\n",