{"title_page": "Pavel Nedv\u011bd", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Pavel Nedv\u011bd\n| image = Pavel Nedv\u011bd.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| alt = Nedv\u011bd wearing the red shirt, blue shorts and blue socks of the Czech Republic\n| caption = Nedv\u011bd playing for the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] at the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|8|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cheb]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| height = 1.77m\n| currentclub = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] (Vice-chairman)\n| position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]<br>[[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Attacking midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1977\u20131985\n| youthclubs1 = TJ Skaln\u00e1\n| youthyears2 = 1985\u20131986\n| youthclubs2 = [[FK Hv\u011bzda Cheb|RH Cheb]]\n| youthyears3 = 1986\u20131990\n| youthclubs3 = [[FC Viktoria Plze\u0148|\u0160koda Plze\u0148]]\n| years1 = 1990\u20131992\n| clubs1 = [[FC Viktoria Plze\u0148|\u0160koda Plze\u0148]]\n| caps1 = 0\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1990\u20131992\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Dukla Prague]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 19\n| goals2 = 3\n| years3= 1992\u20131996\n| clubs3 = [[AC Sparta Prague|Sparta Prague]]\n| caps3 = 97\n| goals3 = 23\n| years4 = 1996\u20132001\n| clubs4 = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]\n| caps4 = 138\n| goals4 = 33\n| years5 = 2001\u20132009\n| clubs5 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n| caps5 = 247\n| goals5 = 51\n| totalcaps = 501\n| totalgoals = 110\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\u20131993\n| nationalteam1 = [[Czechoslovakia national under-21 football team|Czechoslovakia U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1994\u20132006\n| nationalteam2 = [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 91\n| nationalgoals2 = 18\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|CZE}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[UEFA Euro 1996|1996 England]]|}}\n{{Medal|B|[[UEFA Euro 2004|2004 Portugal]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup|1997 Saudi Arabia]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Pavel Nedv\u011bd''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8pav\u025bl \u02c8n\u025bdvj\u025bt|-|Cs-Pavel Nedved.ogg}}; born 30 August 1972) is a Czech retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]]. Described as one of the best footballers of his generation, he is also regarded as one of the most successful players to emerge from the Czech Republic,<ref>{{cite web|title=Pavel Nedved|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/czech_rep/squad/741685.stm|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref> winning domestic and European accolades with Italian clubs [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], including the last [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]], and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], whom he led to the [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final]].\n\nNedv\u011bd was a key member of the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech]] team which reached the final of [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]], during which he attracted international attention. He also captained the national team at [[UEFA Euro 2004]], where they were defeated in the semi-final by eventual champions [[Greece national football team|Greece]], and Nedv\u011bd was named as part of the Team of the Tournament. Furthermore, Nedv\u011bd helped his team qualify for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] for the first time since the breakup of Czechoslovakia. Due to his performances, as well as his quick and energetic runs during matches, Nedv\u011bd was nicknamed \"''{{lang|it|Furia Ceca}}''\" (\"Czech Fury\") by Italian fans and \"The Czech cannon\" in English-language media. His nickname in Czech is ''M\u00e9\u010fa''<ref>{{cite web|title=Pavel \"M\u00e9\u010fa\" Nedv\u011bd vyd\u00e1v\u00e1 v It\u00e1lii svou autobiografii|url=http://sport.tn.nova.cz/clanek/sport/fotbal/dalsi-fotbal/pavel-meda-nedved-vydava-v-italii-svou-autobiografii.html|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> (\"Little Bear\"), stemming from the similarity between his surname and the Czech word for bear, ''Medv\u011bd''.\n\nWinning the Ballon d'Or as [[Ballon d'Or|European Footballer of the Year]] in 2003, Nedv\u011bd was the second Czech player to receive the honour and the first since the breakup of Czechoslovakia. During his career Nedv\u011bd received a number of other individual awards, including the second [[Golden Foot]] award in 2004, [[Czech Footballer of the Year]] (four times) and the [[Golden Ball (Czech Republic)|Golden Ball]] (six times). He was also named by [[Pel\u00e9]] as one of the [[FIFA 100]], and was placed in the [[UEFA Team of the Year]] in 2003, 2004, and 2005. He retired following the [[2008\u201309 Serie A|2008\u201309]] season, after a 19-year professional career. Nedv\u011bd played 501 league matches at club level (scoring 110 goals), and was [[Cap (sport)|capped]] 91 times for the Czech Republic (scoring 18 times).\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Club career ==\n\n=== Czech Republic ===\nBorn on 30 August 1972 in [[Cheb]] and raised in nearby [[Skaln\u00e1]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9j1wbp2t1usC&pg=PA184|title=Historical Dictionary of Soccer|last=Dunmore|first=Tom|date=2011|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810871885|pages=184|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pavelnedved.cz/biografie-2_1.html|title=Pavel Nedv\u011bd: biography|language=Czech|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220172742/http://www.pavelnedved.cz/biografie-2_1.html|archivedate=20 December 2008}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd began his football career in his native Czechoslovakia. A football fan from an early age, he began playing for his hometown club Tatran Skaln\u00e1 in 1977 at the age of five.<ref name=Nedved>{{cite web|title=Pavel Nedved|url=http://www.pavelnedved.cz/|accessdate=8 June 2011|language=cs}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd moved on to [[FK Hv\u011bzda Cheb|Rud\u00e1 Hv\u011bzda Cheb]] in 1985, playing one season before spending five years with [[FC Viktoria Plze\u0148|\u0160koda Plze\u0148]].<ref name=\"Nedved\" /> In 1990, Nedv\u011bd was loaned to [[Dukla Prague]], a club run by the [[Czechoslovak Army|Army]], as part of his [[military service]].<ref>{{cite web|title=S\u00ed\u0148 sl\u00e1vy Dukla Praha 1948 - 2009: Pavel Nedv\u011bd|trans-title=Hall of fame Dukla Praha 1948 - 2009: Pavel Nedv\u011bd|url=http://fkdukla.cz/legendy.asp?legenda=64|language=Czech|publisher=FK Dukla Praha|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> During his first year at Dukla Prague, he played for {{ill|VTJ Dukla T\u00e1bor|cs|VTJ T\u00e1bor (fotbal)}}, a lower division club also operated by the Army. On 28 October 1991, Nedv\u011bd played his first match for Dukla Prague.<ref name=\"konec\" /> He played one season for Dukla in 1991 before finishing his military service, thus ending his loan from Plze\u0148. He then transferred to [[AC Sparta Prague|Sparta Prague]] in 1992.<ref name=jerabek>{{cite book |last=Je\u0159\u00e1bek|first=Lubo\u0161|title=\u010cesk\u00fd a \u010deskoslovensk\u00fd fotbal \u2013 lexikon osobnost\u00ed a klub\u016f|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4ErKtwjzyv8C&lpg=PA132&dq=%22Ne%C4%8Das%2C%20Radim%22&pg=PA132#v=onepage&q=%22Ne%C4%8Das,%20Radim%22&f=false|accessdate=18 March 2012|year=2007|publisher=Grada Publishing|location=Prague|language=Czech|isbn=978-80-247-1656-5|page=132}}</ref> Plze\u0148 was to receive 30% of the transfer fee should Nedv\u011bd transfer to a foreign club.<ref name=\"kosice1\">{{cite news|last=Kellner|first=Tom\u00e1\u0161|url=http://www.praguepost.cz/archivescontent/24100-plzen-battles-sparta-praha-off-the-pitch.html|title=Plzen battles Sparta Praha off the pitch|work=[[The Prague Post]]|date=17 July 1996|accessdate=8 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208060704/http://www.praguepost.cz/archivescontent/24100-plzen-battles-sparta-praha-off-the-pitch.html|archivedate=8 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"kosice2\">{{cite news|last=Bouc|first=Franti\u0161ek|url=http://www.praguepost.cz/archivescontent/25853-soccer-club-incensed-over-cmfs-ruling.html|title=Soccer club incensed over CMFS ruling|work=[[The Prague Post]]|date=30 April 1997|accessdate=8 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304190615/http://www.praguepost.cz/archivescontent/25853-soccer-club-incensed-over-cmfs-ruling.html|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nEarly in his career at Sparta, Nedv\u011bd was sent off three times in just six matches.<ref name=\"konec\">{{cite news |first=Miroslav |last=Nov\u00e1k |title=\nNedv\u011bd: od prvn\u00edho z\u00e1pasu k posledn\u00edmu. P\u0159ijde opravdu konec? |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/nedved-od-prvniho-zapasu-k-poslednimu-prijde-opravdu-konec-po3-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A090528_171752_fot_zahranici_min |newspaper=[[iDNES]] |date=29 May 2009 | accessdate=6 October 2015 |language=Czech}}</ref> With Sparta, Nedv\u011bd won one [[Czechoslovak First League]] title, two [[Gambrinus liga]] titles and a [[Czech Cup]].<ref name=jerabek/> In 1994, he received his first call up to the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic national team]]. His performance at [[UEFA Euro 1996]], including a goal in the group stage against [[Italy national football team|Italy]], attracted attention; despite a verbal agreement with [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]],<ref name=\"kosice1\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Afketsen transfer Nedved grootste teleurstelling|trans-title=Ricochet transfer Nedved biggest disappointment|url=http://www.psv.nl/web/show/id=118705/langid=43/contentid=5959|language=Dutch|publisher=psv.nl|date=26 March 2004|accessdate=8 June 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203005247/http://www.psv.nl/web/show/id=118705/langid=43/contentid=5959|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd moved from Sparta Prague to Italian [[Serie A]] club [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]. Sparta first sold Nedv\u011bd to Slovak club [[1. FC Ko\u0161ice]] (which had the same owner as Sparta) for a 1.5 million [[Czech koruna|CZK]] transfer fee, and immediately, Ko\u0161ice sold Nedv\u011bd to Lazio.<ref name=\"kosice1\" /> Thus Sparta paid only a small fraction of the transfer fee to Plze\u0148.<ref name=\"kosice1\" /><ref name=\"skandaly\">{{cite news |author=val, INT |title=Skand\u00e1ly a zkraty fotbalov\u00e9ho kr\u00e1le Pavla Nedv\u011bda! |url=http://isport.blesk.cz/clanek/svet-hvezd-skandaly/79852/skandaly-a-zkraty-fotbaloveho-krale-pavla-nedveda.html |newspaper=iSport |date=29 April 2009 |accessdate=7 October 2015 |language=Czech}}</ref> After Plze\u0148's protest, the [[Football Association of the Czech Republic|Czech football association]] ordered Sparta to pay Plze\u0148 35 million CZK in compensation.<ref name=\"kosice2\" />\n\nNedv\u011bd signed a four-year contract for a fee of [[Italian lira|\u20a4]]1.2 million.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ghisi |last=Giancarla |title=Nedved alla Lazio, Bierhoff viaggia verso Torino |url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1996/luglio/11/Nedved_alla_Lazio_Bierhoff_viaggia_co_0_9607113572.shtml |newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]] |date=11 July 1996 |accessdate=17 August 2014 |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n=== Lazio ===\nNedv\u011bd made his league debut for Lazio on 7 September 1996 in a 1\u20130 away defeat against [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Taking balls: The numbers game |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Talking+balls%3A+THE+NUMBERS+GAME.-a0120005787 |newspaper=[[Sunday Mail (Scotland)|Sunday Mail]] |publisher=The Free Library |date=1 August 2004 |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"1996\u201397\">{{cite web|title=Italy Championship 1996/97|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital97.html|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref> He scored his first league goal for the club against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] on 20 October 1996, finishing the [[1996\u201397 Serie A|1996\u201397 season]] with seven goals.<ref name=\"1996\u201397\"/> He became an integral part of the side, scoring four goals in three matches early in the 1997\u201398 season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Trow|first=Paul|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4885994.html|title=Football: Barcelona under fire|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=5 October 1997|accessdate=12 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603133030/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4885994.html|archivedate=3 June 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> The club had a 24-match unbeaten streak from November 1997 to April 1998, ending with a league match against [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in which Nedv\u011bd was sent off.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4909629.html|title=Football: Juventus back on top as they end Lazio's unbeaten run|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=6 April 1998|accessdate=12 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604004554/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4909629.html|archivedate=4 June 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> That season, Lazio won the [[1997\u201398 Coppa Italia]] and reached the final of the [[1997\u201398 UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Italy \u2013 Coppa Italia History|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italcuphistfull.html|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UEFA Cup 1997\u201398|url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec199798.html#uefa|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd and Lazio began the 1998\u201399 season with a victory in the [[Supercoppa Italiana]], Nedv\u011bd scoring as the club defeated Juventus 2\u20131.<ref name=ita-super-cup>{{cite web|title=Italy Super Cup Finals|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italsupcuphist.html|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref> He played a role in Lazio's road to the last-ever [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]], scoring against [[FC Lausanne-Sport|Lausanne]] in the first round and in both legs of Lazio's 7\u20130 aggregate quarter-final victory over [[Panionios F.C.|Panionios]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/news/1999/05/18/lazio_route/|title=Lazio's route to the final|work=Sports Illustrated|date=18 May 1999|accessdate=3 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116122316/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/news/1999/05/18/lazio_route/|archivedate=16 January 2014}}</ref> In the [[1999 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup Final]], Nedv\u011bd scored the decisive goal against [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] for Lazio's 2\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas|first=Russell|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/1999/may/20/newsstory.sport1|title=Nedved volley gives Lazio a famous first|work=The Guardian|date=20 May 1999|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> This proved to be the last goal of the tournament, which was later discontinued.<ref name=UEFADIRECT>[http://kassiesa.net/uefafiles/uefadirect/uefadirect-100-2010-08.pdf uefadirect, Issue 100: August 2010], Page 15 \"European Cup Winners' Cup makes its debut\".</ref>\n\nNedv\u011bd was one of the ten highest-paid footballers in the Italian league in 1999.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dobson|first1=Stephen|last2=Goddard|first2=John|title=The Economics of Football|url=https://archive.org/details/economicsoffootb0000dobs|url-access=registration|quote=football pavel nedved -wikipedia.|accessdate=24 January 2014|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=0-521-66158-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/economicsoffootb0000dobs/page/36 36]}}</ref> He played in the [[1999 UEFA Super Cup]] against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at the beginning of the season, where Lazio won the match by a single goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/football/432092.stm|title=Sport: Football Man Utd lose to Super Lazio|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 August 1999|accessdate=12 January 2013}}</ref> The club went on to win the Serie A title and Coppa Italia, completing a [[Double (association football)|domestic double]] in 2000 with Nedv\u011bd's help.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/czech_rep/795854.stm|title=Premiership clubs eyeing Nedved|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 June 2000|accessdate=12 January 2013}}</ref> In 2000, he won the Supercoppa Italiana with Lazio for a second time.<ref name=ita-super-cup/> With [[Sini\u0161a Mihajlovi\u0107]], Nedv\u011bd was one of two Lazio players sent off in the quarter-final of the 2000 Coppa Italia held in December, where the defending champions lost 5\u20133 on aggregate to [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Staniforth|first=Tommy|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5130034.html|title=Football: Nine-man Lazio sent packing from cup|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=13 December 2000|accessdate=12 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614235755/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5130034.html|archivedate=14 June 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref>\n\nNedv\u011bd played [[UEFA Champions League]] football with Lazio, scoring against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in a 2\u20132 draw in the second group stage<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-70768275.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614235836/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-70768275.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 June 2013|title=Madrid end Lazio dream; CHAMPIONS LEAGUE ROUND-UP.(Football)|newspaper=[[Birmingham Evening Mail]]|date=22 February 2001|accessdate=12 January 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> before the Italian side was eliminated. In Lazio's final Champions League match of the season, Nedv\u011bd was criticised by [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] manager [[David O'Leary]] for a challenge on [[Alan Maybury]] (although the referee did not call a foul),<ref>{{cite news|last=Shaw|first=Phil|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5136392.html|title=Football: Mihajlovic dampens the party for Leeds ; Leeds United 3 Lazio 3 \u2013 Yugoslav international's stoppage-time free-kick denies O'Leary's tenacious reserves a deserved victory over Lazio|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=15 March 2001|accessdate=12 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603132935/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5136392.html|archivedate=3 June 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> and he received a three-match suspension from European competitions from [[UEFA]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Tynan|first=Gordon|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5138068.html|title=Football: Greeks deny meddling charge|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=22 March 2001|accessdate=12 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604004532/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5138068.html|archivedate=4 June 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref>\n\nDespite Nedv\u011bd's signing a new four-year contract with Lazio in April 2001,<ref>{{cite news|last=Draper|first=Rob|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-74932285.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603130949/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-74932285.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 June 2013|title=Wes for Kennedy clan.|newspaper=[[The Mail on Sunday]]|date=29 April 2001|accessdate=12 January 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> the club tried to sell him and teammate [[Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n]] that summer, triggering fan protests against club chairman Sergio Cragnotti.<ref>{{cite news|last=Anderson|first=David|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-23856251.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603130551/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-23856251.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 June 2013|title=#23m Veron move expected next week; football news|newspaper=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|date=6 July 2001|accessdate=12 January 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> The players were ultimately sold to Juventus and Manchester United respectively.\n\n=== Juventus ===\n[[File:Football against poverty 2014 - Zidane et Nedved.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Nedv\u011bd ''(left)'' was signed by [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in 2001 to replace [[Zinedine Zidane]].]]\nAfter five seasons with Lazio, Nedv\u011bd was speculatively linked to several clubs (including Manchester United and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]])<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/1341352.stm|title=Nedved targets United switch|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 May 2001|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Montgomery|first=Alex|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-75305790.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603133343/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-75305790.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 June 2013|title=\u00a329m Chelsea in chase for Lazio pair.|newspaper=[[The Mail on Sunday]]|date=4 March 2001|accessdate=12 January 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> before moving to Juventus in July 2001 for 75&nbsp;[[1,000,000,000|billion]]&nbsp;[[Italian lira|lire]] (\u20ac38.7&nbsp;million by fixed exchange rate).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/rubriche/cmercato/200107/05/3b449bd903662/|title=Nedved: ''la Juve l'ho scelta io''|date=5 July 2001|access-date=24 September 2017|work=Rai Sport|publisher=Rai|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2001/giugno/14/Ciao_Juve_Nedved_resta_alla_ga_0_0106144208.shtml|title=Ciao Juve: Nedved resta alla Lazio|date=14 June 2001|access-date=24 September 2017|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|publisher=RCS MediaGroup|publication-place=Milan|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.sslazio.it:80/news/visualizza_news.asp?idnews=325&titolo=1|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010721035749/http://www.sslazio.it/news/visualizza_news.asp?idnews=325&titolo=1|archivedate=21 July 2001|title=Depositati i contratti di cessione di Nedved e Veron|date=18 July 2001|access-date=24 September 2017|publisher=S.S. Lazio|publication-place=Rome|language=Italian|url-status=dead}}</ref> At Juventus, he replaced [[Zinedine Zidane]], who had transferred to Real Madrid that summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/news/newsid=1064964.html|title=Nedved: I can retire happy|publisher=FIFA|date=1 June 2009|accessdate=31 December 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923083602/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/news/newsid=1064964.html|archivedate=23 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd was a regular on Juventus' 2001\u201302 and 2002\u201303 ''[[List of Italian football champions|Scudetto]]''-winning teams.<ref name=NFTprofile>{{NFT player|id=1853}}. Retrieved 3 June 2013.</ref> Although he was a substantial part of the club's championship season in 2003, he was also the subject of controversy. Nedv\u011bd quit the [[Italian Footballers' Association]] in protest of the union's limit on non-[[European Union]] (EU) players;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/2398119/Nedved-at-double-for-Juventus.html#|title=Nedved at double for Juventus|work=The Telegraph|date=17 March 2003|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> his native Czech Republic did not become an EU member until 2004.<ref name=\"Europa History 00\">{{cite web|title=A decade of further expansion|publisher=Europa web portal|url=http://europa.eu/abc/history/2000_today/index_en.htm|accessdate=25 June 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615031714/http://europa.eu/abc/history/2000_today/index_en.htm|archivedate=15 June 2007}}</ref> Although he was instrumental in leading Juventus to the [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final|2003 UEFA Champions League final]] against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]],<ref name=stay2006>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/5195000.stm|title=Nedved decides to stay with Juve|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 July 2006|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> he had to sit out the final due to an accumulation of [[Penalty card#Yellow card|yellow card]]s after his semi-final booking for a foul on Real Madrid midfielder [[Steve McManaman]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Nakrani|first=Sachin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/apr/25/chelsea-champions-league-suspensions|title=Nine other players who have missed major finals due to two bookings|work=The Guardian|date=25 April 2012|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2003, Nedv\u011bd was named World Footballer of the Year by ''[[World Soccer (magazine)|World Soccer]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/3310291.stm|title=Nedved scoops top award|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 December 2003|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> Later that month, he won the [[Ballon d'Or|European Footballer of the Year]] award over [[Thierry Henry]] and [[Paolo Maldini]], the second Czech to win the award after [[Josef Masopust]] in 1962.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/3341645.stm|title=Nedved scoops top award|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 December 2003|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd received further recognition in his home country when he won the 2004 Golden Ball, awarded by Czech sportswriters, for the fifth time in seven years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/czech_rep/3775871.stm|title=Nedved voted Czech's best|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 June 2004|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe 2004\u201305 season was frustrating for the midfielder, who was sidelined for two months by knee and head injuries<ref name=guardian-april2005>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/apr/05/newsstory.sport9|title=Nedved threatens to retire|work=The Guardian|date=5 April 2005|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> and first considered retirement in April 2005.<ref name=guardian-april2005/> Although Juventus won Serie A titles that year and in 2006, the titles were revoked after the ''[[2006 Italian football scandal|Calciopoli]]'' [[match fixing]] scandal. After the 2005\u201306 season, which ended with Juventus' relegation from Serie A despite its first-place finish,<ref name=\"Serie A appeals\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/5215178.stm|title=Punishments cut for Italian clubs|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 July 2006|accessdate=30 July 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060822214348/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/5215178.stm|archivedate=22 August 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> many stars (such as [[Fabio Cannavaro]] and [[Lilian Thuram]]) left the club and the remaining players' future was uncertain.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/5220184.stm|title=Duo to stay at Juve \u2013 Deschamps|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 July 2006|accessdate=14 January 2013}}</ref> After the 2006 World Cup, Nedv\u011bd dispelled rumours about his departure by reiterating his desire to help Juventus regain promotion to Serie A, citing his family and his commitment to the club as reasons for his decision.<ref name=stay2006/> He received a five-match ban after a red card against [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] in December 2006,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/SPORT/football/12/05/italy.nedved/index.html|title=Protest earns Nedved five-game ban|publisher=CNN|date=5 December 2006|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> and repeated his threat to retire.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/nedveda-trest-nastval-muzu-skoncit-rika-fde-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A061206_134251_fot_zahranici_min|title=Nedv\u011bda trest na\u0161tval. M\u016f\u017eu skon\u010dit, \u0159\u00edk\u00e1|language=Czech|trans-title=Nedv\u011bd upset by punishment. He says he could quit|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=6 December 2006|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> However, he remained with the club until the end of the season and scored 11 league goals in the [[2006\u201307 Serie B]].<ref name=NFTprofile/>\n\n[[File:Nedved vs Chinese Olympic Team.jpg|thumb|alt=Two players vying for the ball, with a linesman nearby|Nedv\u011bd playing for Juventus in training, July 2007]]\nFor the 2007\u201308 season, Juventus again played in Serie A. Nedv\u011bd played frequently for the ''Bianconeri'', contributing as the team's first-choice left winger and scoring two goals that season. He was again controversial: in November 2007, his tackle of [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] midfielder [[Lu\u00eds Figo]] broke Figo's [[fibula]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/news/2007/November/6/nedved-apologises-over-figo-tackle| title=Nedved apologises over Figo tackle}}</ref> In April 2008, Nedv\u011bd was hospitalised overnight for a concussion sustained in a collision with [[Roberto Guana]] during a match against [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/nedved-po-otresu-mozku-uz-muze-z-nemocnice-fjx-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A080407_134350_fot_zahranici_ot|title=Nedv\u011bd po ot\u0159esu mozku u\u017e m\u016f\u017ee z nemocnice|language=Czech|trans-title=Nedv\u011bd after concussion can already leave hospital|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=7 April 2008|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nNedv\u011bd scored Juventus' first league goal of the 2008\u201309 season in a 1\u20131 away draw with [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]],<ref name=0809season>{{cite web|title=Italy 2008/09|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital09.html|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref> and scored twice against Bologna in a 2\u20131 away win in October.<ref name=0809season/> On 26 February 2009, Nedv\u011bd announced he would retire at the end of 2008\u201309 season<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/7912535.stm|title=Juve star Nedved to quit football|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 February 2009|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/canadianpress/article/ALeqM5iwGFn-OjURYdAh5GQXB0aTUp9fAA| title=Juventus midfielder Pavel Nedved to retire at end of the season| agency=The Canadian Press| date=26 February 2009| accessdate=26 February 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303024713/https://www.google.com/hostednews/canadianpress/article/ALeqM5iwGFn-OjURYdAh5GQXB0aTUp9fAA|archivedate=3 March 2009}}</ref> to spend more time with his family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1032724.html#nedved+announces+retirement|title=Nedved announces retirement|publisher=FIFA|date=26 February 2009|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> On 10 March 2009, he was substituted due to injury after 12 minutes of the Champions League round of 16 second leg match against Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/7899606.stm|title=Juventus 2\u20132 Chelsea (agg 2\u20133)|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 March 2009|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> Due to his impending retirement and his club's 3\u20132 loss on aggregate, it was his last European match for Juventus. Nedv\u011bd retired at the end of the season, captaining the final match against former team Lazio and setting up [[Vincenzo Iaquinta]]'s goal for a 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Juventus/31-05-2009/juventus-seconda-50472258025.shtml|title=Juventus seconda E Nedved saluta|language=Italian|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|date=31 May 2009|accessdate=31 December 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605072405/http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Juventus/31-05-2009/juventus-seconda-50472258025.shtml|archivedate=5 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== FK Skaln\u00e1 ===\nOn 23 September 2017 it was announced that Nedv\u011bd transferred to FK Skaln\u00e1, based in the village of [[Skaln\u00e1]], Nedv\u011bd's native village. The club plays in the 1. B class of in the [[Karlovy Vary Region]] (7th level of Czech football hierarchy).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irozhlas.cz/sport/fotbal/drzitel-zlateho-mice-v-i-b-tride-pavel-nedve-prestoupil-do-skalne-u-chebu_1709230837_vman|title=Dr\u017eitel Zlat\u00e9ho m\u00ed\u010de v I. B t\u0159\u00edd\u011b. Pavel Nedv\u011bd p\u0159estoupil do Skaln\u00e9 u Chebu|work=iROZHLAS|access-date=3 June 2018|language=cs}}</ref> Chairman of the club had said: \"It was Pavel's dream to play with his son and now it will come true\". He further added that it seems likely that his planned fielding on 2 June 2018 in a home fixture against TJ Ban\u00edk Kr\u00e1lovsk\u00e9 Po\u0159\u00ed\u010di B is a one-off event, due to N\u011bdved's residency in Italy and employment as vice-president of [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fotbal.idnes.cz/pavel-nedved-skalna-navrat-d0p-/fot_dsouteze.aspx?c=A180511_400629_fot_dsouteze_ten|title=Pavel Nedv\u011bd p\u0159estoupil, ve Skaln\u00e9 si spln\u00ed sen. Zahraje si se synem|date=11 May 2018|website=iDNES.cz|access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd was indeed in the starting line-up, but Skaln\u00e1 lost the home fixture 1\u20134, Nedv\u011bd did not score and neither did his son.\n\n== International career ==\nNedv\u011bd began playing for Czechoslovakia national youth teams in 1988, representing his country in the under-15 age group before progressing to 16, 17 and 18.<ref name=jerabek/> In 1992, he made his first appearance on the [[Czechoslovakia national under-21 football team|under-21 team]], playing seven times between 1992 and 1993.<ref name=jerabek/>\n\nThe midfielder debuted for the re-formed [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic national team]] in June 1994 in a 3\u20131 win over the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]].<ref name=2004intlretirement>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/worldcup/news/kind=1/newsid=238209.html |title=Nedved calls time on Czech career|publisher=UEFA|date=24 September 2004|accessdate=20 March 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041030211626/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/WorldCup/news/Kind=1/newsId=238209.html|archivedate=30 October 2004}}</ref> His first major tournament was Euro 1996, where he scored his first senior international goal and helped his team reach [[UEFA Euro 1996 Final|the final]]. He was also part of the Czech team which placed third in the [[1997 FIFA Confederations Cup]], defeating [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in the third-place match. Nedv\u011bd scored two goals during the tournament, both which came during the Czech Republic's 6\u20131 win over the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]] in their final group match, which allowed them to progress to the semi-finals, where they were defeated by eventual champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].\n\n=== Euro 1996 ===\nThe Czech Republic were not expected to make an impact against the favoured [[Germany national football team|Germany]] side in their opening match; Nedv\u011bd missed two scoring chances and was one of ten players to receive a yellow card as Germany won 2\u20130.<ref name=czge1996>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52506/postmatch/report/index.html#germany+overpower+czechs |title=Germany overcome slow-starting Czechs|publisher=UEFA|date=6 October 2003|accessdate=12 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112163914/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52506/postmatch/report/index.html|archivedate=12 January 2013}}</ref> However, he contributed defensively, clearing a goal-bound shot from [[Christian Ziege]] off the [[Association football pitch#Pitch boundary|line]].<ref name=czge1996/>\n\nNedv\u011bd scored his first senior international goal in his nation's Group C match against Italy, putting the Czech Republic in the lead 1\u20130 after four minutes.<ref name=czit1996>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52508/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Bejbl completes Italian job for Czechs|publisher=UEFA|date=6 October 2003|accessdate=12 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112160412/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52508/postmatch/report/index.html|archivedate=12 January 2013}}</ref> Although Italy scored an equaliser during the first half, they were reduced to ten men and the Czech Republic scored again before half-time for a 2\u20131 win.<ref name=czit1996/> Nedv\u011bd played in the third group match, against [[Russia national football team|Russia]], receiving his second yellow card of the tournament as the Czechs tied 3\u20133 to advance to the knockout stage.<ref name=rucz1996>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52510/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Late \u0160micer strike sends Czechs through|publisher=UEFA|date=6 October 2003|accessdate=4 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418142834/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52510/postmatch/report/index.html|archivedate=18 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nDue to a suspension, Nedv\u011bd missed the Czech Republic's quarter-final match against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Docherty|first=John|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-61260143|title=RUBBER CZECHS; Shock troops plan to party all the way to the big final.(Sport)|newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|location=Scotland|date=22 June 1996|accessdate=12 January 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[Questia Online Library]]}}</ref> The Czechs won in his absence and progressed.<ref name=czpt1996>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=223/match=52914/index.html |title=Poborsk\u00fd lob puts Czechs into semi-finals|publisher=UEFA|date=6 October 2003|accessdate=4 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618200318/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=223/match=52914/index.html|archivedate=18 June 2012}}</ref> In the semi-final against [[France national football team|France]], Nedv\u011bd was named [[man of the match]] as the Czech Republic advanced to the final after a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot\u2013out]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Shaw|first=Phil|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4789367.html|title=France are sent home by Kadlec|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=27 June 1996|accessdate=12 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614235829/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4789367.html|archivedate=14 June 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> where he scored his nation's second penalty shot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4789360.html|title=Euro 96 Semi-finals|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=27 June 1996|accessdate=12 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604004548/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4789360.html|archivedate=4 June 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> He and the Czech Republic team lost 2\u20131 in the final to Germany, who scored a [[golden goal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Vogts' triumph over adversity |first=Ken |last=Jones |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/vogts-triumph-over-adversity-1326840.html |work=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=1 July 1996 |accessdate=19 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Euro 2000 ===\nBefore [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]], Nedv\u011bd was unable to train normally due to an ankle injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/czech_rep/783499.stm|title=Czechs counting on Nedved's ankle|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 June 2000|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref> The Czechs' first match (against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]]) saw him and international teammate [[Jan Koller]] hit the [[Goal (sport)|woodwork]] without scoring, before the Dutch scored a controversial penalty to win 1\u20130.<ref name=bbceuro2000>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/czech_rep/801500.stm|title=Republic Czech out|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 June 2000|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> In the second match, against France, he was fouled, where the resultant Czech penalty was converted by [[Karel Poborsk\u00fd]] to even the score at 1\u20131.<ref name=FranceCzech2000>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2000/round=1458/match=64865/report=rp.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130105051122/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2000/round=1458/match=64865/report=rp.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 January 2013|title=Henry fires down Czechs|publisher=UEFA|date=6 October 2003|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref> Despite two shots on goal, Nedv\u011bd could not beat French goalkeeper [[Fabien Barthez]] and France won the match 2\u20131.<ref name=FranceCzech2000/> He played in the third group match, against Denmark; despite the Czechs' 2\u20130 victory, the team was eliminated from the tournament.<ref name=bbceuro2000/> After Euro 2000, Nedv\u011bd took over the national team captaincy from [[Ji\u0159\u00ed N\u011bmec]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Saiver|first=Filip|url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/kapitan-trener-ma-jine-starosti-dnk-/fot_reprez.aspx?c=A010903_224757_fot_reprez_hdv|title=Kapit\u00e1n? Tren\u00e9r m\u00e1 jin\u00e9 starosti...|language=Czech|trans-title=Captain? The manager has other worries...|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=3 September 2001|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Euro 2004 ===\nNedv\u011bd was instrumental in the [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] group stage match against the Netherlands. Two goals down after 19 minutes, he gave a man of the match performance as the Czechs rebounded to win 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hayes|first=Alex|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1861022.html|title=Football: Euro 2004: Nedved masters Dutch in epic encounter|newspaper=[[The Independent|The Independent on Sunday]]|date=20 June 2004|accessdate=1 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604004522/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1861022.html|archivedate=4 June 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> Nine players (including Nedv\u011bd) were rested for the group match against Germany, with the Czechs already qualified for the knockout stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/3787551.stm|title=Germany 1\u20132 Czech Rep|publisher=BBC Sport|date=23 June 2004|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> He received a yellow card, upheld on appeal, in the quarter-final match against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref name=euro04yellow>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/czech_rep/3848561.stm|title=Nedved yellow card stands|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 June 2004|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> This meant Nedv\u011bd would miss the final if he received another yellow card in the semi-final against [[Greece national football team|Greece]].<ref name=euro04yellow/> However, Greece defeated the Czechs and Nedv\u011bd was substituted after a knee injury.<ref name=2004intlretirement/> After their exit from the tournament, Nedv\u011bd announced his retirement from the national team;<ref name=2004intlretirement/> he was named to the Team of the Tournament alongside countrymen [[Petr \u010cech]] and [[Milan Baro\u0161]].<ref name=\"All-star squad revealed\">{{cite news|title=All-star squad revealed|url=http://www.euro2004.com/News/Kind=1/newsId=205742.html|publisher=UEFA|date=5 July 2004|accessdate=5 July 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040707012523/http://www.euro2004.com/News/Kind=1/newsId=205742.html|archivedate=7 July 2004}}</ref>\n\n=== 2006 World Cup ===\nThe midfielder was persuaded by coach [[Karel Br\u00fcckner]] and his teammates to come out of international retirement in time for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA play-off)|2006 World Cup qualification playoffs]] against [[Norway national football team|Norway]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/potvrzeno-v-kadru-pro-baraz-je-i-nedved-dyq-/fot_reprez.aspx?c=A051102_150823_fot_reprez_min|title=Potvrzeno: V k\u00e1dru pro bar\u00e1\u017e je i Nedv\u011bd|language=Czech|trans-title=Confirmed: Nedv\u011bd also in the squad for the play-off|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=2 November 2005|accessdate=2 February 2012}}</ref> in which the Czech Republic qualified for the final tournament for the first time since the breakup of Czechoslovakia.<ref>{{cite news|last=Clarke|first=Gemma|url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/worldcup2006/minbymin/0,,1788308,00.html|title=Czech Republic 0\u20132 Ghana|work=The Guardian|date=17 June 2006|accessdate=4 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060630163049/http://football.guardian.co.uk/worldcup2006/minbymin/0,,1788308,00.html|archivedate=30 June 2006}}</ref> Although Nedv\u011bd's World Cup participation was jeopardised by a June knee injury,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/teams/czech_republic/5060552.stm|title=Nedved hurts knee during training|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 June 2006|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> he was able to play.\n\nThe Czechs won the first match of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] with 3\u20130 against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4852720.stm|title=USA 0\u20133 Czech Republic|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 June 2006|accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref> but key players were injured. They then lost their next two group matches against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] and eventual winners Italy, finishing third in their group.<ref name=ghana2006>{{cite news|last=Jackson|first=Jamie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jun/18/worldcup2006.match1|title=Gyan catches Czechs cold as Ghana gain a glimpse of brazil|work=The Guardian|date=18 June 2006|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=italy2006>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853358.stm|title=Czech Republic 0\u20132 Italy|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 June 2006|accessdate=2 February 2012}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd's apparent goal at the beginning of the second half in the match against Ghana was ruled offside.<ref name=ghana2006/> His shots on goal against Italy were saved by Juventus teammate [[Gianluigi Buffon]].<ref name=italy2006/> Nedv\u011bd again announced his retirement from the international scene before the August 2006 friendly match against [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|Serbia and Montenegro]], in which he made his 91st (and final) appearance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/4795429.stm|title=Nedved calls time on Czech career|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 August 2006|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> He refused to reverse his decision before [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], despite requests from teammates and Br\u00fcckner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/confederationscup/southafrica2009/news/newsid=744669.html|title=Cech urges Nedved to return|publisher=FIFA|date=17 April 2008|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> In the 91 appearances he made for his national side, Nedv\u011bd scored 18 goals.\n\n== Style of play ==\nA complete, tenacious and consistent two-footed player,<ref name=czech-cannon-bbc/><ref name=addio>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Juventus/30-05-2009/nedved-addio-juve-50469731648.shtml|title=Nedved, addio alla Juve|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=30 May 2009|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd frequently played as a left-sided, offensive wide midfielder<ref name=czech-cannon-bbc/> or as a left-[[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] throughout his career,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/pavel-nedved/|title=Nedv\u011bd, Pavel|publisher=Treccani: Enciclopedia dello Sport (2002)|language=Italian|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref> due to his [[Cross (football)|crossing]] ability with his left foot, as well as due to his ability to cut inside and shoot with his right foot, although he was capable of playing anywhere in [[Midfielder|midfield]] due to his offensive and defensive work-rate, as well as his versatility, physicality, and tackling ability, which enabled him to start attacking plays after winning back possession.<ref name=gli>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-pavel-nedved-60830|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Pavel NEDVED|publisher=Tutto Juve.com|language=Italian|author=Stefano Bedeschi|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=indica>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2004/novembre/27/Nedved_indica_pericolo_1_ga_10_04112710163.shtml|title=Nedved indica il pericolo n\u00b0 1|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=27 November 2004|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"irrepressible\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0191-0e6a62b3a4b9-980ee264d318-1000--replacing-the-irrepressible/ |title=Replacing the irrepressible |publisher=UEFA.com |date=27 May 2003 |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Nedved devance Henry\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/sports/nedved-devance-henry-23-12-2003-2004633758.php |title=Nedved devance Henry |publisher=Le Parisien |language=French |last1=S\u00e9verac |first1=Dominique |date=23 December 2003 |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/greece-portugal-dominate-cbc-sports-online-all-star-team-1.489341 |title=Greece, Portugal dominate CBC Sports Online all-star team |work=CBC |date=5 July 2004 |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"storiedicalcio\">{{cite web |url=https://storiedicalcio.altervista.org/blog/pavel_nedved.html |title=NEDVED Pavel: la luce di Praga |publisher=Storie di Calcio |language=Italian |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref> He was also deployed as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] on occasion,<ref name=gli/> as well as in an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfield]] and [[Playmaker|playmaking]] role, or as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|supporting striker]],<ref name=indica/> where he excelled as an [[Assist (football)|assist]]-man due to his excellent [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] ability, passing range and vision.<ref name=gli/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_serie_a/pagemoresco/pagemoresco/pagemoresco.html|title=Buffon, Nedved e Del Piero una squadra con tre fenomeni|publisher=La Repubblica|language=Italian|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref> Primarily known for his powerful shots and volleys from distance,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-23676316.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614235821/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-23676316.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 June 2013|title=Czech coach fears Scots|newspaper=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|last=Broadley|first=Ian|date=19 January 1998|accessdate=12 January 2013}} {{subscription required |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> as well as his stamina,<ref name=gli/> he was also a dynamic player, who was noted for his speed, acceleration, endurance, technique and goal-scoring ability, which often saw him carry the ball and undertake forward surging runs from midfield.<ref name=gli/><ref name=\"Nedved devance Henry\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2004/luglio/01/Nedved_vede_Collina_teme_saltare_co_9_040701114.shtml|title=Nedved vede Collina e teme di saltare un'altra finale|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=1 July 2004|accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"haircut\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/article/778604d2-c61a-45cd-8bca-b608961694ad |title=Noughty Boys: Celebrating Pavel Nedved - much more than just a haircut |publisher=BBC Sport |last1=Victor |first1=Tom |date=19 March 2019 |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"cult\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/8qz9a5/the-cult-pavel-nedved |title=The Cult: Pavel Nedved |publisher=Vice |last1=Magee |first1=Will |date=28 March 2017 |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"key\">{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/campionato-italiano/2003-2004/nedved-the-key_sto502012/story.shtml |title=Nedved the key |publisher=Eurosport |date=1 November 2003 |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/oct/04/europeanfootball.sport |title=Anyone remember Paolo Negro? |work=The Guardian |last1=Richardson |first1=James |date=4 October 2005 |accessdate=29 February 2020 }}</ref> He was also an accurate [[Direct free kick|set-piece]] and [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] taker.<ref name=addio/>\n\nKnown for his trademark long blonde hair, which made him a highly recognisable player on the pitch,<ref name=\"haircut\"/><ref name=\"cult\"/> Nedv\u011bd was nicknamed \"''Furia Ceca''\" (\"Czech Fury\", or also \"[[Blind Fury]]\" in Italian) by Italian fans, who noted his skill, consistency and verve, as well as his stamina, pace, power and determination.<ref name=furiaceca>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/section/czechstoday/pavel-nedved-a-truly-world-class-footballer-comes-into-his-own|title=Pavel Nedved \u2013 a truly world-class footballer comes into his own|work=[[Czech Radio]]|last=Velinger|first=Jan|date=29 October 2003|accessdate=4 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104131135/http://www.radio.cz/en/section/czechstoday/pavel-nedved-a-truly-world-class-footballer-comes-into-his-own|archivedate=4 January 2013}}</ref> In the English-language media, he was called \"the Czech cannon\".<ref name=czech-cannon-bbc>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/football/features/newsid_3750000/3750805.stm|title=Nedved: The Czech Cannon|publisher=BBC Sport|date=n.d.|accessdate=4 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=czech-cannon-pp>{{cite news|url=http://www.praguepost.com/archivescontent/31248-cannon-nedved-aims-for-gold.html|title='Cannon' Nedved aims for gold|work=[[The Prague Post]]|last=Donovan|first=Jeffrey|date=15 December 1999|accessdate=4 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104133009/http://www.praguepost.com/archivescontent/31248-cannon-nedved-aims-for-gold.html|archivedate=4 January 2013}}</ref> His former Lazio boss [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] described him as \"an atypical midfielder, totally complete\".<ref name=czech-cannon-pp/> Despite his ability, Nedv\u011bd's tenacious playing style and disciplinary record also led him to be criticised by some in the sport, who accused him of being excessively reckless in his tackles and of [[Diving (association football)|going to ground too easily]] when challenged.<ref name=\"cult\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2006/febbraio/13/Mancini_finale_nervi_tesi_Nedved_co_9_060213105.shtml|title=Mancini, finale a nervi tesi \"Nedved \u00e8 un simulatore Adesso pensiamo al Milan\"|trans-title=Mancini, tense conclusion \"Nedved is a diver Now we're looking to the match against Milan\"|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|author1=Matteo Garioni|date=13 February 2006|accessdate=12 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Post-playing career ==\n{{Infobox person\n| boards     = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] (vice-[[chairman]])\n| nationality = Czech Republic\n| occupation         = {{ubl|[[Footballer]] (retired)|company director}}\n| awards             = {{ubl|[[FIFA 100]] member|[[Ballon d'Or]] winner|''see full list below''}}\n}}\nNedv\u011bd ran the [[Prague Half Marathon]] in 2010 (his first race at the distance), finishing the course in 1:49:44.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/kenyan-double-in-prague-kosgei-defends-her-ti|title=Kenyan double in Prague\u2026 Kosgei defends her title|work=IAAF|date=27 March 2010|accessdate=15 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115153308/http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/kenyan-double-in-prague-kosgei-defends-her-ti|archivedate=15 November 2014}}</ref> He ran the 2012 [[Prague Marathon]] in a time of 3:50:02 for the 42-kilometre course.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sport.idnes.cz/pavel-nedved-po-prazskem-maratonu-dr3-/atletika.aspx?c=A120513_213944_atletika_par|title=Nedv\u011bd: Maraton m\u011b vystresoval v\u00edc ne\u017e penalta v semifin\u00e1le Eura|language=Czech|trans-title=Nedv\u011bd: the marathon stressed me more than the penalty in the semifinal of Euro |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=14 May 2012|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nNedv\u011bd was named International Personality at the 2012 [[FAI International Football Awards]] in February.<ref name=\"fai-awards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fai.ie/international/senior-men/102385-2012-three-fai-international-award-winners-announced.html|title=2012 Three FAI International Award Winners Announced|work=Football Association of Ireland|date=26 February 2012|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> In January 2013, he was banned from attending Serie A matches for three weeks after he insulted referee [[Paolo Valeri]] during Juventus' match against [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Digby|first=Adam|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1292205/juventus-board-member-pavel-nedved-banned-for-insulting-ref?cc=5739|title=Nedved banned for insulting ref|publisher=ESPN|date=8 January 2013|accessdate=8 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112173947/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1292205/juventus-board-member-pavel-nedved-banned-for-insulting-ref?cc=5739|archivedate=12 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Directorship===\nOn 12 October 2010, [[Exor (company)|Exor]] (the [[Agnelli family]]'s investment company) nominated Nedv\u011bd for a seat on the Juventus [[board of directors]];<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/nedved-se-stal-clenem-predstavenstva-juventusu-turin-ppg-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A101027_165603_fot_zahranici_par|title=Nedv\u011bd se stal \u010dlenem p\u0159edstavenstva Juventusu Tur\u00edn |language=Czech|trans-title=Nedv\u011bd became a member of the board of directors at Juventus Turin |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=27 October 2010|accessdate=4 January 2013}}</ref> he remains a director as of the [[2018\u201319 Juventus F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Directors and Control Bodies \u2013 Profile: Pavel Nedved|url=http://www.juventus.com/en/club/investor-relations/corporate-governance/board-of-directors-and-control-bodies/|publisher=Juventus F.C.|access-date=23 April 2017}}</ref> On 23 October 2015, Nedv\u011bd was appointed as the vice-chairman of the board of directors.<ref>{{citenews|title=Commitment, Passion, Brilliance: The Reasons Pavel Nedved Is so Loved at Juve|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2684270-commitment-passion-brilliance-the-reasons-pavel-nedved-is-so-loved-at-juve|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=30 December 2016|first=Adam|last=Digby}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|title=Company Profile: Juventus Football Club S.p.A.|url=http://www.borsaitaliana.it/companyprofile/pdf/en/546.pdf|publisher=[[Borsa Italiana]]|date=16 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{citenews|title=Nedved named Juventus vice president|url=http://www.juventus.com/en/news/news/2015/-pavel-nedved-named-juventus-vice-president.php|publisher=[[Juventus F.C.]]|date=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nThe son of V\u00e1clav and Anna,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/jak-rostou-nove-hvezdy-fotbalu-dm3-/fot_dsouteze.aspx?c=A060629_081028_fot_dsouteze_rou|title=Jak rostou nov\u00e9 hv\u011bzdy fotbalu?|language=Czech|trans-title=How do the new stars of football grow?|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=29 June 2006|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd had lived with his wife Ivana since 1992.<ref name=family>{{cite web |last=Moravec|first=Martin|url=http://ona.idnes.cz/ivana-nedvedova-muj-zivot-s-pavlem-d5h-/spolecnost.aspx?c=A060615_134639_ona_ony_jup|title=Ivana Nedv\u011bdov\u00e1: M\u016fj \u017eivot s Pavlem|language=Czech|trans-title=Ivana Nedv\u011bdov\u00e1: My life with Pavel|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=16 June 2006|accessdate=4 January 2013}}</ref> The couple have two children, named Ivana and Pavel after their parents.<ref name=family/> The couple had split in 2019 and the exfootballer started dating a 23 years younger parkour rider.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.blesk.cz/clanek/celebrity-ceske-celebrity/614976/fotbalista-pavel-nedved-46-krach-manzelstvi-ted-randi-s-blondynkou-luckou-23.html|title=Fotbalista Pavel Nedv\u011bd (46): Krach man\u017eelstv\u00ed! Te\u010f rand\u00ed s blond\u00fdnkou Luckou (23)|language=Czech|trans-title=Pavel Nedv\u011bd (46): Family Separation! He now dates blond Lucie (23)|work=Blesk|location=Czech Republic|date=6 June 2019}}</ref> Nedv\u011bd's 2010 autobiography was published in Italian as ''{{Lang|it|La mia vita normale: di corsa tra rivoluzione, Europa, e pallone d'oro}}''. It was translated into [[Czech language|Czech]] as ''{{Lang|cs|M\u016fj oby\u010dejn\u00fd \u017eivot}}'' and released in the Czech Republic in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chuchma|last=Josef|url=http://zpravy.idnes.cz/jaka-je-knizni-zpoved-fotbalisty-pavla-nedveda-prumerna-p2e-/zpr_archiv.aspx?c=A110508_121118_kavarna_chu|title=Jak\u00e1 je kni\u017en\u00ed zpov\u011b\u010f fotbalisty Pavla Nedv\u011bda? Pr\u016fm\u011brn\u00e1|language=Czech|trans-title=What is the book confession of footballer Pavel Nedv\u011bd like? Average|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|location=Czech Republic|date=8 May 2011|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Career statistics ==\n\n=== Club ===\nSources: League matches,<ref name=NFTprofile/> Coppa Italia stats at Juventus,<ref name=myjuve>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjuve.it/players-juventus/pavel-nedved-388.aspx|title=Pavel Nedv\u011bd|publisher=myjuve.it|date=n.d.|accessdate=4 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518004738/http://www.myjuve.it/players-juventus/pavel-nedved-388.aspx|archivedate=18 May 2011}}</ref> European competition stats<ref>{{cite web|first=Marcel|last=Haisma|title=Pavel Nedved \u2013 Matches in European Cups|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/nedved-in-ec.html|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Dukla Prague]]\n||[[1991\u201392 Czechoslovak First League|1991\u201392]]\n|[[Czechoslovak First League|First League]]\n|19||3||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||19||3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[AC Sparta Prague|Sparta Prague]]\n||[[1992\u201393 Czechoslovak First League|1992\u201393]]\n|First League\n|17||0||||||5<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"CWC\">All appearance(s) in [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]]</ref>||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||0\n|-\n||[[1993\u201394 Czech First League|1993\u201394]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Czech First League|Ga